Authors: Gerard Mendoza, Matthew Muranaka¶

Abstract¶

For this project, we were given a 15-dimensional dataset with 1.2 million observations each with a class label; 1, 2, or 3 with the goal being to build a pipeline that processes, models, and predicts the class label any given sample belongs. Through data analysis, we found the data to be split into three clusters where at least two labels were dispersed within each cluster. By leveraging heatmaps to perform correlation analysis, we found relatively low correlation between each of the features and class labels, suggesting the nonlinear nature of the data. Further, similarity analysis indicated many observations to be cosine and euclidean similar while carrying different labels. With this in mind, we decided to induce nonlinear models like random foresting, optimizing parameters by conducting a grid search. We also attempted a multi-stage classification process, turning the multinomial classification task into two separate binary tasks with the hopes of producing a better performing model. Through all of this, our models maximized at around 73% accuracy for a test set, carrying persisting issues in classifying between the data in each cluster.

After looking through the SKLearn Preprocessing documentation, we are debating between the StandardScaler and MinMaxScaler. We are most experienced with these two and believe either one will be sufficient in normalizing the data. In order to decide which one to use, we consulted stack overflow and the discussion provided a pretty clear explanation between the two. This made us rethink using a standard scaler, ultimately seeing the min-max scaler as the best option for our type of data. Standard scaler was mentioned as a useful tool for features that follow a normal distribution but most of our features are multimodal. Further, from the results of the agg call, we know the ranges of the variables which is needed when MinMax Scaling.

Using the MinMaxScaler, since all of the variables have negative values, we are going to scale the values into a range of [-1, 1].

Explanation of the Heatmap and Top Features¶

The heatmap represents the pairwise Pearson correlation coefficients between all features and the target variable (Class).

Values range from -1 to 1:

1.0: Perfect positive correlation (as one feature increases, the other increases proportionally).
-1.0: Perfect negative correlation (as one feature increases, the other decreases proportionally).
0.0: No linear relationship between the variables.

The diagonal is always 1.0 because each feature is perfectly correlated with itself.

Now looking at all our correlations with Class, we see that it is all relatively low with a max of .30. This showed us our features have weak to moderate linear relationships. We were really hoping that we could single out features with higher correlation values so to provide us with more predictive power for the target variable but since no single feature strongly predicts the Class, we are forced to think harder and do more work with combining features or using non-linear methods to capture interactions. It was a good start to expirement with logistic regression for benchmarking. An ideal model would have to capture the more complex interactions and handle all this multicollinearity. Next steps may be to start testing with models like Random Forests or XGBoost for interpretability and non-linear learning.

With this type of result for the class distribution with the principal components, I chose to determine the cosine similarity between features and produce the amount of extremely similar observations that differ in Class label.

I did a bunch of research towards efficiently gaining the cosine similarity between the most observations but due to the nature of this type of algorithm, had to limit the size to 36,000 samples which is 3% of the total dataset, otherwise my program will fail due to memory overusage.

I used scipy.spatial.distance over the sklearn's cosine similarity function due to its ability to handle larger dataset sizes. I am not exactly sure about the process that utilizes RAM better but it works.

X_train_np = X_train.to_numpy()

similarity_matrix = 1 - squareform(pdist(X_train_np, metric='cosine'))

high_similarity_pairs = np.argwhere(similarity_matrix > threshold)

high_similarity_pairs = high_similarity_pairs[high_similarity_pairs[:, 0] < high_similarity_pairs[:, 1]]

similar = np.empty((0, 2))
for i in high_similarity_pairs:
    if (y_train.iloc[i[0]] != y_train.iloc[i[1]]):

With that being said, I am going to compute similar vectors using euclidean distance with the idea that magnitude is the key difference between observations belonging to a certain class.

Smote¶

To combat the class imbalances, we researched into a Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique, SMOTE. The technique involves a combintaion of over-sampling the minority while undersampling the majority. As a result, the dataset will contain a more balanced distribution of class labels greater than only under-sampling the prevalent class (1).

In [11]:
import logging
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
import time

logging.basicConfig(level=logging.INFO, format='%(asctime)s - %(message)s')
start_time = time.time()
X_train = df_1_train.drop(columns=['Class', 'Class_i']).to_numpy()
X_test = df_1_test.drop(columns=['Class']).to_numpy()

y_train = df_1_train['Class'].to_numpy()
y_test = df_1_test['Class'].to_numpy()
logging.info(f"Original training data shape: {X_train.shape}, {y_train.shape}")
logging.info(f"Original test data shape: {X_test.shape}, {y_test.shape}")

# 1. Handle Class Imbalance with SMOTE
logging.info("Applying SMOTE to balance the dataset...")
smote_start = time.time()
smote = SMOTE(random_state=11)
X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
logging.info(f"SMOTE completed in {time.time() - smote_start:.2f} seconds.")
logging.info(f"Resampled training data shape: {X_train_resampled.shape}, {y_train_resampled.shape}")

logging.info("Training Random Forest model with tuned hyperparameters...")
train_start = time.time()
rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(
    n_estimators=200,  # Increased number of trees
    max_depth=20,      # Limit tree depth for efficiency
    min_samples_split=5,  # Reduce overfitting
    max_features='sqrt',  # Use square root of features at each split
    random_state=11
)
rf_model.fit(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled)
logging.info(f"Random Forest training completed in {time.time() - train_start:.2f} seconds.")

logging.info("Generating predictions on test data...")
predict_start = time.time()
y_pred = rf_model.predict(X_test)
logging.info(f"Predictions completed in {time.time() - predict_start:.2f} seconds.")

logging.info("Evaluating the model...")
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
classification_report_str = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)

logging.info("Random Forest Accuracy: %.4f" % accuracy)
logging.info(f"Confusion Matrix:\n{conf_matrix}")
logging.info(f"Classification Report:\n{classification_report_str}")
logging.info(f"Total runtime: {time.time() - start_time:.2f} seconds.")

This time we got a slight improvement of about .1% but it is still not as good as logistic regression. To make things easier, we opted for a binary classification strategy. Looking at the confusion matrix, our model is pretty good at separating class 2 from class 1 and 3. This led to some experimentation with a multi stage model.

Hierarchical Classification¶

Earlier we created a premature logistic regression model with its main purpose to discover the amount of time it would take to fit and validate a model with a large amount of training and test data. With that being said, the simple model actually produced very surprising results, differentiating between class 1 and 2 at a perfect rate. While this model is useless in a practical setting, because an actual model will have to also identify which observations are class 3, we believe it might lead us somewhere.

Before, following through with this process, we would like to state we are aware such processes are usually for classification tasks with a large amount of classes. We understand this type of model will probably not be the final submission but we are interested in the results that may occur.

In a research entry for the Journal of Royal Statistical Society, Allan Gordan describes a Direct Optimization algorithm for hierarchical classification which utilizes a predefined criterion between classification levels 2. We believe this algorithm is most relevant to our goals because we already know which parent classification task we want to achieve.

Prior to model construction, we foresee problems with the parent classification task since the classes 1 and 3 or 2 and 3 may not be easily seperable. This problem is one of the main focuses of the article and the reason such a classification process is such computationally expensive proces. Luckily, we are tasked with a ternary classification task which doesn't require a deep class dendrogram.

In order to achieve such a process, we are first going to split the full scaled dataset into a training and test set. We have chosen a 70 to 30 train/test split because with such a process, we believe it would be best for a greater amount of testing. For the training set, we are going to create a new binary column, Class_i, where 0 values equate to class 1 and 2 while 1 values equate to class 3.

We now have the new temporary class which we will be training on. To start, we will try random foresting in order to classify Class_i. Upon predictions of not Class 3, we will apply logistic regression again to separate class 1 and 3.

This test has shown potential but we can improve on how we set up the model still. We want to keep working on doing the double random forest so the next experiment involves finding the most optimal settings for the model. We try a full grid search and apply a 3 fold cross validation test on it - this would mean 243 combinations of tests made 3 times each and estimated to take 50 hours. Grid search would help us systematically tune our model's hyperparameters to improve performance by automating the search process. It could also maybe reduce our overfitting but these are all just words, lets see how we did:

import logging
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from time import time

# Set up logging
logging.basicConfig(level=logging.INFO, format='%(asctime)s - %(message)s')
logger = logging.getLogger()

# Define parameter grid
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 300, 500],
    'max_depth': [10, 15, 20],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 5, 10],
    'max_features': ['sqrt', 'log2', None]
}

# Calculate total fits
total_combinations = (
    len(param_grid['n_estimators']) *
    len(param_grid['max_depth']) *
    len(param_grid['min_samples_split']) *
    len(param_grid['min_samples_leaf']) *
    len(param_grid['max_features'])
)
total_fits = total_combinations * 3  # 3 is the number of cross-validation folds

logger.info(f"Total parameter combinations: {total_combinations}")
logger.info(f"Total fits to perform (including CV): {total_fits}")

# Start timing
start_time = time()

# Set up Grid Search with verbose output
grid_search = GridSearchCV(
    RandomForestClassifier(random_state=11, class_weight="balanced_subsample"),
    param_grid,
    cv=3,
    scoring='f1_weighted',
    n_jobs=-1,
    verbose=3  # This will log progress of fits
)

logger.info("Starting Grid Search...")
grid_search.fit(X_train_not_class_2, y_train_not_class_2)
logger.info("Grid Search complete.")

# Best parameters and model
best_rf = grid_search.best_estimator_
logger.info("Best Parameters: %s", grid_search.best_params_)

# End timing
end_time = time()
logger.info("Total time for Grid Search: %.2f seconds", end_time - start_time)

Removing Eucliden Similar Observations¶

With the optimal random forest parameters, we explore the abilities of removing vectors that are close together in euclidean distance but differ in class label. The idea behind this model is to remove hypothetical noise from wrongly labelled or improper observations.

Note drop_indices are the indices of observations less than 0.05 euclidean distance from each other that have different class labels.

Model Validation¶

Most model validation was done alongside model training. You will notice the main evaluation metric used during model training was accuracy score which considers the percentage of predictions correctly labeled over the amount of test samples. Many of the models testing is accompanied with a confusion matrix. We decided to print confusion matrices because of its human readibility, allowing us to determine what type of missclassifications occurs during the testing process.

Below is the original random forest classifier create during the model exploration stage. You will notice the algorithm never incorrectly predicts Class 2 for Class 1 labels and vice versa. Further, the model rarely predicts Class 2 for Class 3. These are the key reasons we decided to try a multistage classification process.

While certain models considered precision, recall, and f-score, we did not value these metrics as high as accuracy. The reason for this is the lack of knowledge about the dataset. Due to the unknown nature of the variables and class labels, we are unsure which classification label to value most. Consider the cost of false of Class 3 labels to be much higher than that of Class 1 or 2. If this was the case, we would regard precision or f-score as crucial metrics to consider when fitting a model. A similar situation can be said about recall and its high value for false negatives, and many other metrics which aim to evaluate the different rows/columns of the confusion matrix.

You will notice the model is indifferent between the three clusters, these clusters are the same that were found in the Data Analysis portion. In order to gain a better insight into the performance between each cluster, we are going to perform KMeans clustering in order to determine which cluster each observation belongs to and evaluate each clusters performance using the optimized random forest model.

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

# train
cluster_amount = 3

for i in range(cluster_amount):
    cluster_indices = np.where(cluster_predict == i)[0]
    X_test_cluster = X_test[cluster_indices]
    y_test_cluster = y_test.iloc[cluster_indices]
    
    y_pred_cluster = rfc.predict(X_test_cluster)
    print("Cluster", i)
    print(confusion_matrix(y_test_cluster, y_pred_cluster))
    print(accuracy_score(y_test_cluster, y_pred_cluster), "\n")

Through this evaluation, we have determined the main issue with our classification stems from the accuracy of the bottom-most cluster where accuracy is about the same as randomly choosing between the two labels in that cluster. In comparison, the two top-most clusters produced accuracies above 75%.

Looking at the confusion matrix for each cluster it appears each cluster rarely or never predicts against the main label. In cluster 0, Class 3 is predicted in all but four of the observations. In cluster 1 and cluster 2, Class 2 and Class 1 is always predicted respectively.

Conclusion¶

Overall, our models were able to maximize the classifications with the separable data through our different techniques of testing. We explored different models both linear and nonlinear while applying ways that can balance the data itself like PCA, SMOTE, and similarity analysis. Our models saw success in classifying certain labels while experiencing persistent struggles with identifying Class 3 labels. Class 2 had a high recall and f1 score leading us to focus more on what we really struggled with which was separating class 1 and 3. Our issues came from how consistent all our testing came to be. Despite changing up the models, tuning all the parameters, balancing the data, and hours of optimization we would be fixed around 72~73% accuracy. This made it hard to expand on ideas we had and constrained us on data visualization and understanding. Through all our graphs we saw most of our difficulties rest in how much overlap there was between class 1 and 3. A majority of the features had heavy overlap causing them to be redundant and the 2 features that were supposed to be the most important still had a good portion of overlap.

If we had another chance at classifying this dataset, we would attempt to model the data through a discretized process. The results of the cluster analysis and misclassification distribution indicate our models experienced difficulty with truly identifying between the classes. One possible way to improve results is splitting the problem into three separate problems, one for each distinct cluster, and repeating the process for each cluster of observations. While initial model exploration struggled with predicting within clusters, performing data analysis by cluster rather than the whole dataset may lead to performance improvements.

With knowledge of the data and the meaning of a sample’s class label, model performance could be optimized towards certain classes, maximizing situational metrics. Further, there would be a greater understanding of the data analysis and the results from features.
